An email will be going out from Florence 1 Schools with bus information for your student/s. Elementary information will be sent Thursday evening and middle/high school will be sent Friday. Please make sure to check your inbox and spam folders. If you have not received an email by Monday, please send an email to transportation@fsd1.org or call 843-673-1118.

If the district did not have an email address associated with your student/s in the system, you will be receiving a letter in the mail with bus information.

The national office of Parents as Teachers has informed the Florence 1 Schools Parent as Teachers home visiting program that it has demonstrated fidelity (high- standards) in all areas of its annual performance measures report.

The home visiting program works with preschool parents to provide knowledge and resources to prepare their preschool children (from prenatal through kindergarten) for a stronger start in life and greater success in school.

According to Melanie McMillan, the Parents as Teachers services are available to families virtually during the present COVID 19 Pandemic.

The program is located under Departments. Then, click Parent Education Services and Request Services.

For more information, call the Florence 1 Schools Parent Education Services Office 843-758-6871.

#F1SParentEducationServices #F1SPreschool

post_text:
Bass Team Qualifies for the B.A.S.S. National Championship

From the Desk of Jeremy Trussell:
In everything that has taken place with sports in 2020 we finally finished the bass season Saturday with the state championship. Even though we did not take first this year in the state, the team of Matt Brault and Jackson Salley finished 2nd in the final standing of the SC High School Bass Challenge Trail.

This finish has qualified them for the B.A.S.S. National Championship to be held in October in Paris, TN on Kentucky Lake.

Both of these anglers are rising seniors and great young men. The school and district should be proud to have these young men represent them in October.

Jeremy Trussell
South Florence/Southside Bass Team Advisor

post_text:
The Project Search Transition-to-Work Program is a unique, business-led, one-year employment, student-preparation program that takes place entirely in the workplace
During the 2019-20 school year, Florence 1 Schools partnered with McLeod Regional Medical Center (Florence), Pee Dee AHEC, South Carolina Vocational Rehabilitation Department, and the South Carolina Department of Disabilities and Special Needs to implement the first year of the Project Search McLeod Program.
Through this collaboration, Project Search held its first graduation ceremony, celebrating the preparation of the following students: Markus Arthur, Bryce Alford, Joshua Sweeney, TySean McLeod, and Danielle Douglas.
Back row left to right: Brian Denny, Assistant Superintendent Exceptional Education; Bryce Alford, Stacy Bakas, Community Based Training Coordinator; Joshua Sweeney, Markus Arthur, Nancy Brown, Project Search Instructor; Anne Filyaw, Transition Coordinator.

Front Row left to right: Matthew Peake, Pee Dee AHEC Health Careers Program Coordinator; Danielle Douglas, and Tysean McLeod.

Registration is now open for the 2020-2021 school year! The registration portals for both new and returning students can be found on the district’s registration webpage, www.f1s.org/registration (Spanish forms can be found there as well). Parents and guardians must complete a separate online registration form for each child who will be attending Florence 1 Schools for the upcoming year.

Due to current social distancing measures, parents who require a meeting with the staff of the Office of Attendance and Zoning must make an appointment. Summer hours for Attendance and Zoning are Monday through Thursday, 9:00 a.m. until 3:00 p.m. All district offices are closed on Fridays. If you need to make an appointment, please call 843-673-1164.

Any student who is registered, with proper and complete Proof of Residency documentation fully uploaded, by July 1 will receive their schedule and/or homeroom teacher assignment the week of July 6th. Students who register after that date will not receive this information until the district holds onsite registration the week of July 20-24.

Congratulations to Katrina Rouse!

Last year, Social Studies Coordinator Katrina Rouse created lessons in conjunction with the University of South Carolina and the Library of Congress, where her teaching lessons were featured.

Rouse recently received notice that her lessons and primary source album will be featured in the Library of Congress' Teaching Primary Sources and on the home page of the Teaching Primary Sources Network as a trending topic.

For more information go to: https://tpsteachersnetwork.org/

post_text:
Florence 1 Schools is seeking Health Science Teachers for various locations. The instructional duties include: therapeutic and development pathways of the health science career cluster. The instructor will provide healthcare-specific knowledge and skills, both academic and technical, necessary for transition-to-work based learning experience in healthcare. Students are to become CNA certified.

Qualifications:
Must have a minimum of an Associate's Degree in nursing and a minimum of two years of full-time work experience as a Registered Nurse OR Bachelor’s degree in nursing and six-months of full-time work experience and hold a current and valid Registered Nursing License.

190 Day Contract, Teacher Pay Scale

For questions contact Ashley Watson, Director of Recruitment and Certification, awatson@f1s.org. Visit www.f1s.org to view this and other available positions or to apply. #TeachF1S #SeekingTopTalent

This is our final week of #F1SMoveYourWay2020. Don't let the rain stop your progress; keep moving!! Also, don't forget to email your picture to mrollins@fsd1.org for a chance to win one of our prizes.

We want to hear from you! Visit the F1S Facebook MoveYourWay2020 photo album to like and/or comment on your favorite pics. The areas of judging will be: Most Likes, Most Extreme, Most Humorous and Most Creative. (The judging panel will consider all comments.) Winners will be announced June 1, 2020.

shared_text:
Coker University
May 18 at 3:45 PM ·

Coker University awarded two full-tuition 2020 Excellence in Teaching scholarships to two deserving Teachers of the Year: a M.Ed. in Literacy Studies scholarship was awarded to Sarah Watts-Spivey, an elementary teacher at York Preparatory Academy and York Preparatory’s 2018-2019 Teacher of the Year, and a M.Ed. in Curriculum & Instructional Technology scholarship was awarded to Nichole Scipio, Biology and Project Lead the Way (PLTW) biomedical science teacher at West Florence High School and 2019-2020 Florence One School District Teacher of the Year.

post_text:
Florence 1 Schools held its Male and Female Athlete of the Year ceremonies today with student nominees representing each of the three high schools.

Each high school nominated one male and one female athlete, and a committee of local sports editors and directors selected the district winners which were announced at the Poynor Building.

Nominees included South Florence’s Alexis Kirby (softball) and Cameron Harper (football); West Florence's Lauren Gordon (volleyball/track) and Wyatt Emerson (football/tennis/golf); also, Wilson’s Loyal McQueen (cross country/girls’ basketball) and Yavin Smith (football/track and field).

Wilson High School’s Loyal McQueen and Yavin Smith received the Florence 1 Schools 2020 Female and Male Athlete of the Year Awards, respectively

shared_text:
Sneed Middle School
May 12 at 10:10 AM ·

Congratulations to our Sneed Middle School 2019-2020 Teacher of the Year, Mrs. Lynn Howard!!!

Mrs. Howard has been a Science teacher here at Sneed for 7 years now. In addition to her regular teaching duties, she is the head of our award-winning 4-H Club and assists with our Environmental Club.

Sneed Middle School has an established Honeybee Apiary thanks to a grant Mrs. Howard, a certified beekeeper, won for us. More recently, we received a Champions of the Environment grant for a Wildlife Oasis on our campus. She has put in countless hours of her own time working on these projects, and has even planted a 4-H Food Plot for her students to tend!

Thank you, Mrs. Howard, for all you do for our school and our students! Congratulations on a much-deserved award!

More recently, we received a Champions of the Environment grant for a Wildlife Oasis on our campus. She has put in countless hours of her own time working on these projects, and has even planted a 4-H Food Plot for her students to tend!

Thank you, Mrs. Howard, for all you do for our school and our students! Congratulations on a much-deserved award!

post_text:
Our celebration of National Nurses Week continues! Today, meet Linda Ellis.
Linda Ellis is a school nurse at West Florence High School. She is currently in her third year as a Knight. Prior to serving at West Florence she worked as a Title One Health Screening Nurse for Florence 1. Nurse Ellis has worked in the district for 14 years!
A family member was Ellis’ inspiration for becoming a nurse.
“I grew up with a disabled sister and watching nurses care for her inspired me to pursue my degree in the field of nursing,” Ellis said. “Being a nurse also allows me to embrace my nurturing spirit.”
Ellis said that caring for the physical needs of students at her school is just one part of what she does.
“School nursing is more than just treating the physical injuries,” Ellis said. “We also incorporate their psychosocial needs as well. It is always a great feeling when you can improve a student's well being and earn their trust.”
Happy National Nurses Week Nurse Ellis!

post_text:
How are Florence 1 educators engaging students online?

For the juniors in my class, I create video lessons with various ways for them to take notes (hand written, Powerpoint template, google docs).
We are currently in our 3rd online unit, and I have received so much positivity from my students on how our lessons are going. They appreciate my hard work as much as I appreciate theirs. We have lost no time; the biology learning continues, and we will be ready for our IB biology exam next spring!
Kelly Clouse, Biology Teacher, Wilson High School
(To view other responses, check out Thursday's issue of Today's Update).
